'''Damendorf Man''' is a German squashed [[bog body]] discovered in 1900 in the See Moor at the village [[Damendorf]] in [[Schleswig-Holstein]], Germany.
==Display and Examination== [[File:Damendorf Man.jpg|thumb|The Damendorf Man is well known for being flattened by the peat bog he was found in.]] The remains are currently on display at the Archäologisches Landesmuseum. Professor [[P.V. Glob]] wrote that the man died in 300 [[Common Era|BCE]]. What is unique about this bog body is the fact that the weight of the peat in the bog had flattened his body.<ref name="Robinson">{{cite book|last=Gill-Robinson|first=Heather|title=The Iron Age Bog Bodies of the Archäologische Landesmuseum Schloss Gottorf|year=2005}}</ref> Only his hair, skin, nails and his few clothes were preserved, along with traces of some bones.<ref name="Robinson" /><ref>[http://www.mummytombs.com/bog/damendorf.htm Damendorf Man] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721194519/http://www.mummytombs.com/bog/damendorf.htm |date=2011-07-21 }}. Mummytombs.com. Retrieved on 15 September 2011.</ref> He was found with a leather belt, shoes, and a pair of breeches.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.archaeology.org/online/features/bog/clothing2.html Archaeology Magazine – Bodies of the Bogs – Clothing and Hair Styles]. Archaeology.org. Retrieved on 15 September 2011.</ref>
==Other finds== Prior to the Damendorf Man's discovery, the remains of what are [[List of bog bodies#Damendorf I|believed to be a woman]] were found in 1884 in the same bog. The clothing of the corpse is all that remains. A girl was discovered in 1934, dating to 810 BCE.<ref>{{cite book|last=Van der Sanden|first=Wijnand|authorlink = Wijnand van der Sanden|title=Through Nature to Eternity|year=1996|page=104}}</ref> ==References== {{commons|Mann von Damendorf}}
