{{Suicide sidebar}}

'''Suicide in Cameroon''' has increased rapidly in the last 10 years, although health officials faced challenges assembling official statistics because suicide is considered a [[taboo]] in most parts of Africa.<ref>[http://allafrica.com/stories/201209110742.html allAfrica.com: Cameroon: World Suicide Rate Increases by 60 Per cent<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Suicide trends in Cameroonian society can be measured as a [[developing world]] problem due to socio-cultural and family relationship mechanisms. Although no governmental data is available to the causes of [[suicide]] in Cameroon, depression has been a documented causes in regard to traditional African initiation rights and worries about contracting HIV/AIDS.<ref>International encyclopedia of adolescence: A-J, index, Volume 1 p.135</ref>

Under Cameroonian Law, to commit suicide itself is not illegal, as is reporting on a suicide in the media, however publication of the suicide of a [[Minor (law)|minor]] is an offence. Government treatment of physiological disorders relating to suicide severely lacks funding.<ref>Criminal Law in Cameroon: Specific Offences  By Carlson Anyangwe p.286</ref> According to the [[World Health Organization]], there were only 2 [[psychiatric hospitals]] and just 115 beds in such hospitals out of a population of 19.9 million. Cameroon does not have a mental health plan, nor does it have a policy as such.<ref>http://www.who.int/mental_health/evidence/atlas/profiles/cmr_mh_profile.pdf</ref>

The Ministry of Health carried out a 9-year study in the [[Guidiguis]] health district between 1999 and 2008, a rural province in the north of the country. The most frequently used suicide method in the region was the ingestion of toxic agricultural chemicals and the suicides main cause were mainly attributed to ongoing chronic illness (31.9%), with sexual and marital conflicts (25.5%), [[witchcraft]] (14.9%), financial problems (8.5%) being the cause in other cases. The study concluded that suicide in rural [[Cameroon]] is not unusual and the capacity of mental health services in rural Cameroon is virtually non-existent.<ref>[http://europepmc.org/abstract/MED/23786446/reload=0;jsessionid=7obdhXfqa97YrbSyimsk.12 Profile of suicide in rural Cameroon: are health systems doing enough? - Abstract - Europe PubMed Central<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

